#compdef hive_router
# ============================================================================
# hive_router - GraphQL Federation router/
#                gateway for production
#                microservice architectures
#                (Rust, MIT)
#
# Author : The Guild
#           (theguild.dev; commercial
#           GraphQL ecosystem
#           organization stewarding Hive
#           Router + GraphQL Hive +
#           GraphQL Mesh + GraphQL Code
#           Generator + graphql-tools)
# Upstream: https://github.com/graphql-hive/router
# crates.io: hive-router (binary:
#             hive_router)
#
# `hive_router` is The Guild's open-source
# GraphQL Federation router - a high-
# performance gateway for orchestrating
# GraphQL queries across multiple subgraph
# services that implement Apollo Federation
# Spec v2. The router accepts incoming
# GraphQL operations + plans + executes
# them against the federated subgraph
# network, returning unified GraphQL
# responses.
#
# Architecture:
#   1. **Federation v2 spec compliant**
#      (full Apollo Federation Spec v2
#      support with @key + @requires +
#      @provides + @external + @inaccessible
#      + @override + @shareable + @tag
#      + @link directives)
#   2. **Query planning** (analyzes
#      incoming GraphQL operations +
#      generates execution plans across
#      subgraphs to minimize round-trip
#      latency)
#   3. **Persisted documents support**
#     (clients can pre-register query
#     documents + send hashes at runtime
#     for security + performance)
#   4. **JWT authentication** (built-in
#     JWT auth with JWKS support for
#     downstream service authorization)
#   5. **Plugin system** (Rust trait-
#     based plugins for custom
#     middleware + auth + telemetry +
#     rate limiting; plugin examples
#     in plugin_examples/)
#   6. **OpenTelemetry integration**
#     (distributed tracing + metrics
#     export via OTLP)
#   7. **Subscriptions** (WebSocket-
#     based GraphQL subscriptions +
#     HTTP callback subscriptions)
#
# Distinguishing features vs alternatives
# (Apollo Router + Cosmo Router + Gateway):
#   - **MIT-licensed** (Apollo Router
#     v2 has Elastic License 2.0
#     restrictions; hive_router is
#     fully permissive)
#   - **The Guild stewardship** (The
#     Guild has been the canonical
#     GraphQL ecosystem maintenance
#     org since ~2017; broad GraphQL
#     tooling experience)
#   - **Hive Console integration**
#     (built-in metrics + schema
#     registry integration with The
#     Guild's GraphQL Hive platform)
#   - **Rust performance** (built on
#     ntex web framework for high-
#     throughput async serving;
#     mimalloc allocator for memory
#     efficiency)
#   - **Plugin SDK in Rust** (Apollo
#     Router uses Rhai scripting +
#     YAML; hive_router uses native
#     Rust traits for compile-time
#     plugin development)
#
# Use cases:
#   - **Apollo Federation deployments**
#     (multi-team microservice
#     architectures with team-owned
#     GraphQL subgraphs unified into
#     a single supergraph)
#   - **GraphQL gateway replacement**
#     (drop-in replacement for Apollo
#     Router for teams wanting MIT
#     license)
#   - **Self-hosted GraphQL platform**
#     (pair with Hive Console for
#     schema registry + metrics)
#   - **Multi-tenant GraphQL backends**
#     (route + transform GraphQL
#     queries across tenant subgraphs)
#
# Usage:
#   hive_router
#
# Configuration via environment variables:
#   ROUTER_CONFIG_FILE_PATH        - path
#                                     to
#                                     YAML
#                                     config
#                                     file
#                                     (required)
#
# The router has no CLI flags - all
# configuration is via YAML config file
# specified via ROUTER_CONFIG_FILE_PATH.
# This 12-factor app design aligns with
# Kubernetes + Docker deployment
# patterns.
#
# Example invocations:
#   # Run with explicit config path
#   ROUTER_CONFIG_FILE_PATH=/etc/router.yaml \
#     hive_router
#
#   # Or via .env file
#   echo 'ROUTER_CONFIG_FILE_PATH=/etc/router.yaml' \
#     > .env
#   hive_router
#
#   # Default config location (typically
#   # ./router.yaml in the working
#   # directory)
#   hive_router
#
# Configuration file (YAML):
#   ```yaml
#   # Supergraph schema source
#   supergraph:
#     path: ./supergraph.graphql
#     # or load from Hive registry:
#     # registry:
#     #   endpoint: https://app.graphql-hive.com
#     #   key: ${HIVE_CDN_KEY}
#
#   # HTTP server
#   http:
#     port: 4000
#     host: 0.0.0.0
#
#   # JWT authentication
#   jwt:
#     jwks_url: https://auth.example.com/.well-known/jwks.json
#     required: true
#
#   # Persisted documents
#   persisted_documents:
#     allow_arbitrary: false
#     manifest_url: https://cdn.example.com/queries.json
#
#   # CORS
#   cors:
#     allow_origins:
#       - https://app.example.com
#     allow_credentials: true
#
#   # Subgraphs (when not using
#   # supergraph SDL)
#   subgraphs:
#     users:
#       url: http://users-service:4001/graphql
#     products:
#       url: http://products-service:4002/graphql
#
#   # Plugins
#   plugins:
#     - name: rate_limit
#       config:
#         requests_per_second: 100
#     - name: telemetry
#       config:
#         otlp_endpoint: http://otel-collector:4317
#
#   # Telemetry (Prometheus + OpenTelemetry)
#   telemetry:
#     prometheus:
#       enabled: true
#       endpoint: /metrics
#     tracing:
#       otlp:
#         endpoint: http://jaeger:4318
#
#   # Validation rules
#   validation:
#     max_aliases: 10
#     max_depth: 15
#     max_directives: 50
#   ```
#
# The async-graphql lane is built on
# `async-graphql` (declared verbatim at
# upstream lib/graphql-tools/Cargo.toml
# HEAD as a direct dep, imported by the
# `graphql_tools` workspace crate for
# GraphQL schema introspection + query
# validation + execution), the canonical
# Rust GraphQL library by Sunli + the
# async-graphql team - github.com/async-
# graphql/async-graphql.
#
# Note: hive_router uses async-graphql
# selectively for schema-related
# operations; query execution uses The
# Guild's own hive_router_query_planner +
# hive_router_plan_executor crates. The
# router's primary GraphQL infrastructure
# is in-house, with async-graphql providing
# canonical Rust GraphQL primitives where
# applicable.
#
# async-graphql/async-graphql is the
# de-facto canonical Rust GraphQL library:
#   - **Spec-compliant** (GraphQL June
#     2018 spec + Draft 2024 features)
#   - **Async-first** (built on tokio;
#     uses futures for all resolver
#     functions)
#   - **Macros for ergonomics** (#[Object]
#     + #[SimpleObject] + #[Union] +
#     #[Interface] + #[Enum] derive-
#     style macros for schema definition)
#   - **Subscription support** (WebSocket
#     + Server-Sent Events transports
#     for real-time queries)
#   - **DataLoader integration** (built-in
#     DataLoader for N+1 query
#     prevention)
#   - **Schema-first + code-first**
#     (supports both approaches; SDL
#     parsing + code-defined types)
#   - **OpenAPI + protobuf interop**
#     (cross-format API bindings)
#   - **3,800+ stars on github.com/
#     async-graphql/async-graphql**
#   - **~5,000 reverse-deps on
#     crates.io** (the canonical Rust
#     GraphQL stack)
#
# async-graphql's distinguishing position
# vs Rust GraphQL alternatives:
#   - async-graphql/async-graphql (Sunli
#     + team): canonical; async-first;
#     spec-compliant; THIS AXIS
#   - juniper (graphql-rust/juniper):
#     older Rust GraphQL library; sync
#     by default; less feature-rich
#     than async-graphql; ~5k stars but
#     less actively maintained
#   - cynic (obmarg/cynic): GraphQL
#     CLIENT library (not server);
#     code generation from schema
#   - graphql-client (graphql-rust/
#     graphql-client): older client
#     library
#
# Sunli is the original author of
# async-graphql + lead maintainer.
# Sunli is a Chinese Rust developer
# who has contributed extensively to
# async-graphql + tide-rs (the async
# web framework) + many other Rust
# async ecosystem libraries.
#
# Sunli's broader Rust ecosystem
# footprint:
#   - **async-graphql/async-graphql**
#     (THIS AXIS; canonical Rust
#     GraphQL)
#   - **http-rs/tide** (older async
#     web framework; predecessor to
#     axum in many use cases)
#   - **futures-async-stream**
#     (async stream utility)
#
# Sunli's role in Rust is *async
# ecosystem + GraphQL infrastructure*.
# His async-graphql library has become
# the canonical Rust GraphQL server
# framework in the 2020s as Rust async
# adoption matured.
#
# The Guild's broader role: The Guild
# is one of the most prolific GraphQL
# ecosystem maintenance organizations,
# stewarding:
#   - **graphql-tools** (canonical
#     GraphQL utility library across
#     languages)
#   - **GraphQL Code Generator**
#     (canonical schema → typed
#     client code generator)
#   - **GraphQL Mesh** (cross-API
#     unification: REST + gRPC + ODBC +
#     ... → GraphQL)
#   - **GraphQL Hive** (commercial
#     GraphQL schema registry + metrics
#     platform)
#   - **GraphQL Inspector** (schema
#     diff + breaking change detector)
#   - **GraphQL ESLint** (linting for
#     GraphQL documents)
#   - **GraphQL Yoga** (GraphQL server
#     for Node)
#   - **GraphQL Hive Router** (THIS
#     AXIS; Rust GraphQL Federation
#     gateway)
#
# The Guild + Sunli joining the
# canonical-Rust cohort at the *GraphQL
# ecosystem maintenance + canonical
# library author* level extends the
# pattern of *coordinated multi-vertical
# GraphQL ecosystem stewardship*.
#
# Multi-axis canonical-Rust author/org
# cohort extension (now spanning even
# more distinct authors):
#   - + Sunli + async-graphql team +
#     The Guild (async-graphql + Hive
#     Router + graphql-tools + many
#     other GraphQL libraries; THIS
#     AXIS; canonical Rust GraphQL +
#     foundational GraphQL ecosystem
#     stewardship)
#
# hive_router uses the broader GraphQL
# ecosystem stack:
#   - **async-graphql**: schema
#     introspection + query validation
#   - **graphql-tools**: schema
#     stitching + transformation
#   - **hive_router_query_planner**:
#     The Guild's Rust query planner
#     (Federation v2 spec compliant)
#   - **hive_router_plan_executor**:
#     The Guild's Rust execution
#     engine
#
# This is the canonical use case for
# Rust GraphQL libraries in production
# infrastructure: high-performance
# GraphQL gateway routing where every
# millisecond matters + Rust's memory
# safety eliminates entire CVE classes
# that have affected JavaScript-based
# Apollo Router historically.
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 293 :: GraphQL libraries
#              (GraphQL spec compliant
#              servers + schema definition
#              + query planning + Federation
#              support + subscription
#              transports)
# Round 1577 :: Rust slot 1 of 4 :: OPENS Axis 293
#
# Cross-language canonical library family
# for this axis (proposed):
#   Rust    : async-graphql/async-graphql - Sunli +
#                                            async-
#                                            graphql
#                                            team
#                                            (canonical
#                                            Rust
#                                            GraphQL;
#                                            async-
#                                            first;
#                                            macro
#                                            ergonomics)
#   Go      : 99designs/gqlgen          - Patrik
#                                          Adler +
#                                          99designs
#                                          team
#                                          (canonical
#                                          Go
#                                          GraphQL;
#                                          schema-
#                                          first;
#                                          codegen
#                                          approach)
#   TS/Node : graphql/graphql-js        - Meta/
#             OR                          Facebook +
#             apollographql/apollo-server   GraphQL
#                                          spec
#                                          authors
#                                          (canonical
#                                          Node
#                                          GraphQL;
#                                          spec
#                                          reference)
#
# GraphQL is the *modern alternative to
# REST* for API design:
#   - **Created by Facebook 2012**
#     (open-sourced 2015; standardized
#     2018)
#   - **Strongly-typed schema** (vs
#     REST's untyped JSON)
#   - **Single endpoint** (all queries
#     go to /graphql vs REST's
#     resource-per-URL)
#   - **Client-driven shape** (clients
#     request exactly what they need;
#     no overfetching)
#   - **Adoption**: Facebook + GitHub +
#     Twitter + Netflix + Airbnb +
#     Shopify + many others
#
# Each canonical library provides:
#   - GraphQL spec-compliant parsing +
#     execution
#   - Schema definition (code-first or
#     schema-first)
#   - Resolver function infrastructure
#   - Query validation
#   - Subscription support
#   - Federation/composition support
#     (some libraries)
#
# Use-case spectrum for this axis (so far):
#   - hive_router (Rust, async-graphql):
#     The Guild's GraphQL Federation
#     router for production microservice
#     gateways
# ============================================================================

_hive_router() {
    # hive_router is configured entirely
    # via environment variables (primarily
    # ROUTER_CONFIG_FILE_PATH); no CLI
    # flags
    _arguments \
        '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]'
}

_hive_router "$@"
